<p>The product designs and functionality went through many, many iterations. Some included tools far richer than the more recent version of the site. However, we found that users quickly lost interest, unable to see the â€˜so what.â€™ Other versions included simplified visuals with no ability to inspect the data behind it. Users lost interest in these as too simplistic, unable to see the â€˜now whatâ€™. Ultimately, we found that in order to extend beyond the early adopters, you have to make meaning, show your work,/and/ recommend next steps.</p>

<p><em>Hereâ€™s the what, how, so what, now what.</em></p>

<p>Humans are naturally suspicious of new information, especially information that contradicts beliefs, tremendously so when these suggestions come from machines. Showing our work, how we came to those conclusions, increased userâ€™s trust in the system. However, the most effective prototypes used social proof.</p>

<p>â€˜Youâ€™ll feel better if you run at nightâ€™ causes skepticism.</p>

<p>â€˜See, heres the dataâ€™ lowers skepticism slightly.</p>

<p>â€˜It works, just ask your friend Tomâ€™ virtually eliminates skepticism.</p>

<p>Social proof wins. In many cases, with zero supporting data.</p>

<p>While I canâ€™t delve deeply into the details, these suggestions for â€˜life optimizationâ€™ are the primary focus of further development at Basis as well as throughout the wearable space. Everyone is excited by the â€˜Quantified Selfâ€™ movement, but most are really interested in the â€˜Qualified Selfâ€™ (whether they know it or not). In other words, lots of folks think itâ€™s neat to track steps. But they have unspoken intentions about how this information might help them. Only geeks find interest in the pure data. Everyone wants to jump past the â€˜got dataâ€™ to the â€˜made it meaningful.â€™</p>
